    "whatIsOptimisticOracle": "What is an Optimistic Oracle?",
    "whatIsOptimisticOracleAnswer": "An optimistic oracle is a mechanism that assumes data is correct unless challenged. Data is published on-chain with a challenge period during which anyone can dispute it. If no dispute, the data is finalized; if disputed, UMA token holders vote on the correct value.",
    "howToParticipate": "How to Participate in UMA Network?",
    "howToParticipateAnswer": "You can participate in three ways: 1) Become a validator, stake UMA tokens and provide data verification services; 2) Participate in dispute voting to help resolve data disputes; 3) As a developer, integrate UMA oracle into your applications.",
    "howDisputesResolved": "How are Disputes Resolved?",
    "howDisputesResolvedAnswer": "When someone disputes data, a voting period is triggered. UMA token holders can vote on the correct value. After voting ends, the value decided by the majority is adopted. Honest voters receive rewards, while malicious actors are penalized.",
    "howToEarnStaking": "How to Earn from Staking?",
    "howToEarnStakingAnswer": "Validators earn rewards by providing accurate data verification services. Rewards come from protocol inflation and dispute resolution fees. The more you stake and the more actively you participate, the more rewards you earn.",
    "umaVsOthers": "How is UMA Different from Other Oracles?",
    "umaVsOthersAnswer": "UMA is an optimistic oracle, different from active verification oracles like Chainlink. UMA can verify any type of data, not just price data. Verification costs are lower, but a dispute mechanism is needed to ensure security.",
    "securityGuarantee": "How Does UMA Ensure Security?",
    "securityGuaranteeAnswer": "UMA ensures security through economic incentives. Validators need to stake tokens and are penalized for providing incorrect data. The dispute resolution mechanism ensures malicious behavior cannot profit. As long as there is one honest validator, the system works correctly.",
